Preparation: Calculate the forward returns for stocks and market indices¶

In [2]:
csv_path = "0 Data/"
stockclose = "StockClosePrice"
indexclose = "IndexClosePrice"

forward_day = 5 # this should depend on your rolling period

# calculate the forward returns
stock = pd.read_csv(csv_path + stockclose + ".csv", index_col = 0, parse_dates = True)
stockforward = stock.shift(periods = -forward_day, freq = None, axis = 0)
# 5Dforward(t) = (close_price(t+5)-close_price(t))/close_price(t)
stockforwardreturn = (stockforward - stock) / stock
print(stockforwardreturn.head())
stockforwardreturn.to_csv(os.path.join(csv_path, '5DForward.csv')) #stock

# In the simulation, 
# you should also calculate indices returns, 
# and hedge your portfolio with any one of them.
index = pd.read_csv(csv_path + indexclose + ".csv", index_col = 0, parse_dates = True)
indexforward = index.shift(periods = -forward_day, freq = None, axis = 0)
indexforwardreturn = (indexforward - index) / index
print(indexforwardreturn.head())
indexforwardreturn.to_csv(os.path.join(csv_path, 'mkt_5DForward.csv')) #mkt

#factor_folder = "0 Data/0 Sample_factors/" # I am only using several sample factors here. You should try all factors
factor_folder = "0 Data/0 ALL_factors/"
factor_list = list(set(os.listdir(factor_folder)) - set(['.DS_Store']))
factor_list.sort()
factor_list

# Read all factor files
# Remeber to Z-score the factor values to remove the scale differences
dfs = []
i = 0
for factor in factor_list:
    dfs.append(factor)
    df = pd.read_csv(factor_folder + factor , index_col = 0, parse_dates = True)
    dfs[i] = (df - df.mean()) / df.std() 
    i = i + 1

#Construct each stock's dataset
data_trans=[]
for i in range(return_cut.shape[1]):
    temp = return_cut.iloc[:,i:i+1]
    data_trans.append(temp)
    for j in range(len(dfs)):
        temp = pd.concat([temp,dfs[j].iloc[:,i:i+1]],axis=1)
    temp.set_axis(factors, axis='columns', inplace=True)
    temp['index']=range(1,len(temp)+1)
    temp['index']=temp['index'].apply(lambda x:str(i+1)+','+str(x))
    temp.set_index(['index'],inplace=True)
    data_trans[i] = temp

#concat all the stock's data together
temp=data_trans[0].copy()

for i in range(1,len(data_trans)):
    temp = pd.concat([temp,data_trans[i]],axis=0)

Training Factors¶

In this part, we use four different ways to train factors and get a new one:linear regression, support vector machine regression, random forest regression and XGboosting. In order to get a better result, we also use the GridSearchCV fuction to do the cross validation and find the better parameter.

SVR¶

Since the outputnew factor is continuous number, we choose SVR instead of SVM to do this part, which we believe is more appropriate. The parameter of SVR mainly include kernel, C and gamma. Firstly, we use four different type of kernel with their default parameter to fit the model first. And by comparing the output plot generated by backtest file, we think using 'linear' can fit the model more accurate and get a better result. Then we use GridSearchCV to verify our guess and also choose the appropriate 'C'. Since 'linear' does not have the parameter 'gamma', we didn't add the 'gamma' into GridSearchCV. Hoewever, GridSearchCV output a different result: using 'rbf' and C as 0.1. We made two attempts: both using C as 0.1 but choosing different kernel: 'rbf' and 'linear'. Comparing the backtest output, 'linear' seems still perform better. So we choose linear in the end.

In [8]:

from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

Bonus Question 2¶

Trading frequency¶

Here we try to change the trading frequency from 5 days to 2 days.

Trading frequency means that the how often we change our portfolio. The default number is 5 days. Correspondingly, we decide to choose two days as the new cycle time, and we assume that shorter period will generate more return.We need to pay attention that if we change the trading frequency, we need to change the cycle time in backtest into two days as well.

In [17]:
csv_path = "0 Data/"
stockclose = "StockClosePrice"
indexclose = "IndexClosePrice"

forward_day = 2 # this should depend on your rolling period

# calculate the forward returns
stock = pd.read_csv(csv_path + stockclose + ".csv", index_col = 0, parse_dates = True)
stockforward = stock.shift(periods = -forward_day, freq = None, axis = 0)
# 5Dforward(t) = (close_price(t+5)-close_price(t))/close_price(t)
stockforwardreturn = (stockforward - stock) / stock
print(stockforwardreturn.head())
stockforwardreturn.to_csv(os.path.join(csv_path, '2DForward.csv')) #stock

# In the simulation, 
# you should also calculate indices returns, 
# and hedge your portfolio with any one of them.
index = pd.read_csv(csv_path + indexclose + ".csv", index_col = 0, parse_dates = True)
indexforward = index.shift(periods = -forward_day, freq = None, axis = 0)
indexforwardreturn = (indexforward - index) / index
print(indexforwardreturn.head())
indexforwardreturn.to_csv(os.path.join(csv_path, 'mkt_2DForward.csv')) #mkt

def singlefactor(factor,factor_path_all,Type,direction,fwdrtn,mkt_index,cycle, start, end, quantile,win,year, statuslimit):
    factor_path = os.path.join(factor_path_all, factor + '.csv')

    Type1 = "LS"
    B = Backtestlite(factor_path, direction, fwdrtn, mkt_index, factor_path_all, cycle, start, end, quantile, statuslimit)
    B.run(Type1)

    # Drawing
    pic = DrawPicture(factor,direction, B.data,  B.fwdrtn, B.data.index , mkt_index,  B.rtn_data, B.coverage, B.turnover, factor_path_all, Type1)    
    pic.main(win,year,B.rtn_data.columns)
    
# Calculate performances and do the plot
singlefactor(factor,factor_path_all,Type, direction,fwdrtn,mkt_index,cycle, start, end, quantile,win,year, statuslimit)

Trading Feasibility¶

In reality, when there is sharp change happening on return of a single stock in Mainland China A share market, up to 10% or -10% in a day, the exchange institute will make a sudden stop on trading, and the limit will continue during the whole day. Although the trading actually can be completed after a long queue rather than being totally prohibited, in our homework, we assume that no trading can be done for that stock on the day in this situation. Considering about this condition, firstly, we calculated the changing rate of the return on the trading day, with the formulation: rate =(close_price(t)-open_price(t))/open_price(t), and save the result in the file with format of csv named by 'rate of stock price changing.csv'

Differentiated Weights¶

We read the backtestlite.py carefully, and find that in the file the stock are assumed to be trading equally. We want to give more weight to Q_5 as we believe Q_5 perform much better since stocks in Q_5 have higher stock return. So we change the defuction in the backtestlite.py.

What's more, since the XGBoost has the best performance, we use XGBoosting as model and draw a plot of the different factor sorting by importance from highest to lowest. It turns out that marketvalue is important one.

Base on this, we read some paper and find that it is reasonable to combine market value and return stock and give stocks with higher marketvalue more weight.

In [ ]:
# The following is the modified part about changing the status limit.

mrt_value = pd.read_csv(os.path.join(factor_folder, "mrt_value.csv"), index_col = 0, parse_dates = True).loc[start:end][::cycle]

# For a certain quantile (choose_quantile), return weight (dataframe)
    def getQuantileWeight(self, choose_quantile):
        weight = pd.DataFrame(0., index = self.rank.index, columns = self.rank.columns) 
        weight[(self.rank <= ((choose_quantile * 1.0) / self.quantile)) & (self.rank > ((choose_quantile - 1) / self.quantile))] = 1
        #We want to give more weight to stocks with higher market value in each quantile
        rank_mkt_value = weight.mul(mkt_value, axis = 0)
        weight = rank_mkt_value.div(rank_mkt_value.sum(axis = 1), axis = 0)
        return weight

Also, we consider assign weights to each stocks base on sharpe ratio which also take risk into consideration. However, due to time limit, it is hard for us to write code about this part. Usually the method of calculating the Sharpe rate is like thisTo simplify the calculation process, we use a month as a cycle and choose U.S. Treasury Interest Rate as rf. We assume st as stock price in t month and calculate ln(st/s(t-1)), and denote this as return, and then calculate the average return, Er and get the sharp ratio as (Er-rf)/std(return).
